<DOC><DOCNO> AP890320-0147 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NR-03-20-89 2031EST</FILEID><FIRST>r i AM-ComputerEspionage     03-20 0169</FIRST><SECOND>AM-Computer Espionage,0174</SECOND><HEAD>Authorities Say KGB Has Obtained Computer Passwords</HEAD><DATELINE>WIESBADEN, West Germany (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   West German authorities Mondaywarned businesses and public institutions that Soviet intelligencehas obtained passwords and codes to gain access into their computers.   A statement by the Federal Criminal Office said the codesapparently were passed to the Soviet KGB by three West German``hackers'' arrested this month.   The three are suspected of selling thousands of codes andpasswords from Western military and research computers to Sovietintelligence agents.   Police authorities investigating the case have determined thatthe hackers allegedly planned to break into or succeeded in breakinginto many other computers, the statement said.   ``The KGB is capable of gaining full access to computer data ofbusinesses and public institutions,'' it added.   It said obtaining computer codes and passwords has become a ``newtype of espionage by the East.''   When the three were arrested, authorities said they had cracked amajor spy ring and warned of a new dimension in Soviet-blocespionage.</TEXT></DOC>